<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Lobbyists for some of the nation's largest technology companies will use the new agreement to oppose efforts in Congress to broaden the rights of consumers, such as explicitly permitting viewers to make backup copies of DVDs for personal use or to copy songs onto handheld listening devices. <br>
<br>
&quot;How companies satisfy consumer expectations is a business decision that should be driven by the dynamics of the marketplace and should not be legislated or regulated,&quot; the agreement said. <br>
<br>
Holleyman said leading technology companies believe the 1998 Digital Millennium Copyright Act, which restricts what consumers can do with digital music and movies, is &quot;generally working as it was intended.&quot; <br>
<br>
from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&amp;u=/ap/20030114/ap_en_mu/downloading_music_15" target="top"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Yahoo's article</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This agreement is about making it harder for people to download music which they aren't entitled to, and instead of sticking to that point they're trying to step on every consumer's neck with an iron heel.  Consumer rights are not meant to be outlined by government legislature, true, but neither are they a business decision in and of themselves.  When will these idiots get a clue and stop trying to keep people from doing legitimate things with goods purchased.  <br>
<br>
I don't have the right to make money off the music I've bought or put my name on something and sell it as my own, but I do have the right to listen to or watch my property as I see fit.  If that means burning a copy of ten CDs onto one so I don't have to carry 10 CDs to work with me when I want to listen to music or listening to the MP3s off my hard drive because I believe my CD drive is noisey, then that's my right as a consumer.  Consumer rights have been eroded a lot over the last few years, and now we get to hear that lobbyist groups for these money grubbing weasels are going to make sure consumers do not get back what rights were taken away from them?  Frankly that sucks.  <br>
<br>
As for the DMCA, I honestly want to know what planet these people are living on.  One case against a person who made software to decode DVDs just got thrown out simply because the court said the law could not be applied to him due to jurisdiction (can't try someone for a law in California if the person lives in Texas and hasn't been to CA).  Most people on the consumer end of that law consider it one of the worst pieces of legislature in recent years.  What else can you call a law that would put you in prison for using a magic marker on a CD to circumvent the copy protection?  I call it laughable.<br>
<br>
Honestly, if they believe the DMCA is doing its job, then why are they trying to make sure consumers don't get any rights back?  A better question might be why we should trust the RIAA and the tech industry to satisfy our expectations for their products without any legislation or regulation to keep them in check?  The RIAA already lost in court on allegations of price fixing, and the tech industry is rife with suits stemming from anti-trust.  Why should I trust a software company that puts spyware on my computer in the cleverly worded guise of &quot;digital license management&quot;?  They only tell you they're putting in license management somewhere within the 16 page license agreement which only a fraction of us can stomach to read, and when you uninstall the program, the license management garbage you don't know about hasn't been removed from your computer.  Yeah, there's a lot of love and trust between consumers and the industries right now.  *snorts* <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#77839D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub141.ezboard.com/beverquestpeople.showUserPublicProfile?gid=drenesh>Drenesh</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://pages.prodigy.net/bestsmileys1/emoticons1/reaper2.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Hot Shot!</span><br>  Posts: 133<br> <font color=#F7E5C3>(1/14/03 9:37:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub141.ezboard.com/feverquestpeoplefrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=806.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Why should we trust you?</span><hr size=1> All it is, is a knee-jerk reaction to the internet &quot;boom&quot;, and how it has changed business models.<br>
